Tariquidar

value.value: An anthranilamide derivative with multidrug resistance properties.  Tariquidar non-competitively binds to the p-glycoprotein transporter, thereby inhibiting transmembrane transport of anticancer drugs.  Inhibition of transmembrane transport may result in increased intracellular concentrations of an anticancer drug, thereby augmenting its cytotoxicity. (NCI04)

Y 90 Monoclonal Antibody Lym-1

value.value: A radioimmunoconjugate of a murine monoclonal antibody, MoAb Lym-1, labeled with yttrium 90 (Y-90). MoAb Lym-1 recognizes an epitope of the histocompatibility antigen HLA-DR, which is over-expressed on most B-cell lymphomas. Y-90 MoAb Lym-1 delivers Y-90 radionuclide directly to tumor cells that express HLA-DR antigen, thereby this agent may be used in radioimmunotherapy of cancers.

Y 90 Monoclonal Antibody M195

value.value: A radioimmunoconjugate of humanized M195 monoclonal antibody (MoAb) conjugated with isotope yttrium 90. MoAb M195 is reactive with the cell surface antigen CD33, a glycoprotein found on myeloid leukemia blasts and early hematopoietic progenitor cells but not on normal stem cells. This radioimmunoconjugate emits beta particles that causes cytotoxicity in tumor cells and has both imaging and therapeutic uses.

Organism Modification

value.value: Techniques used for deliberately altering the genetic material of an organism in order to make them capable of making new substances or performing new or different functions.

label.value: Yttrium Y 90 Monoclonal Antibody MN-14

value.value: A radioimmunotherapeutic monoclonal antibody (MN-14) directed against tumor-associated carcinoembryonic antigen (CEA) and chelated to the radioisotope yttrium-90 (Y 90). Yttrium 90 monoclonal antibody MN-14 binds to tumor cell expressing CEA, delivering a cytotoxic dose of beta radiation. (NCI04)

label.value: Tumor Cell Graft

value.value: The transplantation of cultured, or separated, tumor cells.

label.value: Knock-out

value.value: Inactivation of specific genes by homologous recombination. Knockouts are often created in laboratory organisms such as yeast or mice so that scientists can study the knockout organism as a model for a particular disease.

label.value: Knock-in

value.value: Replacement of a gene by an altered version of the same gene using homologous recombination resulting in a gain of function. One example of a knock-in is deletion of a coding sequence of a gene in a mouse and then replacing it with human coding sequences.

label.value: Radiation-Induced Change

value.value: Techniques used for altering the genetic material of an organism by exposure to ionizing radiation.

label.value: Chemical-Induced Change
Retrovirus Insertion Modification

value.value: Organism modification caused by change in its genetic material brought about by retrovirus. The retrovirus constructs a DNA version of its genes using a special enzyme called reverse transcriptase and this DNA then becomes part of the cell's genetic material.

label.value: Rat Transgene

value.value: Modification of a rat by transgenic techniques.
